<subSubSection box="[952,1316,1873,1900]" pageId="11" pageNumber="692" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="11.[952,1316,1873,1900]" box="[952,1316,1873,1900]" pageId="11" pageNumber="692">
<taxonomicName authority="Agassiz, 1835" authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1835" box="[952,1114,1873,1899]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pycnodontidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pycnodontiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="692" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Pycnodontidae</taxonomicName>
indet. (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1261,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[132,143,1544,1561]" captionTargetBox="[133,1456,215,1501]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[133,1456,215,1501]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 6. — Actinopterygian remains from Angeac-Charente: A, vomerine dentition of cf. Micropycnodon sp. (ANG M-69) in occlusal view; B, C, detailed view of an isolated vomerine tooth of cf. Micropycnodon sp. (ANG M-28) in (B) anterior and (C) occlusal views; D, E, isolated tooth of Pycnodontidae indet. (ANG M-50) in occlusal (D) and lateral (E) views; F, isolated tooth of Pycnodontidae indet. (ANG M-59) in lateral view. Scale bars: A, 2.5 mm; B, C, F, 500 µm; D, E, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902047/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="692">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
D-F)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="693" pageId="11" pageNumber="692" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[813,1455,1938,2028]" box="[813,957,1938,1964]" pageId="11" pageNumber="692">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[813,1455,1938,2028]" lastBlockId="12.[131,776,1523,2028]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="693" pageId="11" pageNumber="692">
A second pycnodontiform taxon is represented by beanshaped to suboval teeth with a transverse groove or depression and one or two lateral tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[499,563,1523,1549]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[132,143,1544,1561]" captionTargetBox="[133,1456,215,1501]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[133,1456,215,1501]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 6. — Actinopterygian remains from Angeac-Charente: A, vomerine dentition of cf. Micropycnodon sp. (ANG M-69) in occlusal view; B, C, detailed view of an isolated vomerine tooth of cf. Micropycnodon sp. (ANG M-28) in (B) anterior and (C) occlusal views; D, E, isolated tooth of Pycnodontidae indet. (ANG M-50) in occlusal (D) and lateral (E) views; F, isolated tooth of Pycnodontidae indet. (ANG M-59) in lateral view. Scale bars: A, 2.5 mm; B, C, F, 500 µm; D, E, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902047/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
D-F). This taxon is also present in the Purbeckian facies of Cherves-de-Cognac, and has been described as “tooth morphotype 7” by 
<bibRefCitation author="POUECH J. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; CAVIN L. &amp; POYATO- ARIZA F. J." journalOrPublisher="Cretaceous Research" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" pagination="32 - 43" part="55" refId="ref46928" refString="POUECH J., MAZIN J. - M., CAVIN L., POYATO- ARIZA F. J. 2015. - A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications. Cretaceous Research 55: 32 - 43. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2015.01.001" title="A Berriasian actinopterygians fauna from Cherves-de-Cognac, France: biodiversity and palaeoenvironmental implications" type="journal article" year="2015">
Pouech 
<emphasis box="[132,186,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">et al.</emphasis>
(2015
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 8b). A very similar and likely congeneric form has also been described from the Wealden facies of southern 
<collectingCountry box="[241,335,1682,1708]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">England</collectingCountry>
as 
<taxonomicName box="[372,506,1682,1709]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pycnodontidae" genus="Coelodus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[372,467,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">Coelodus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M." box="[523,766,1682,1708]" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" pagination="872 - 896" part="113" refId="ref49895" refString="SWEETMAN S. C., GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M. 2014. - A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 113: 872 - 896. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2011.0109" title="A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England" type="journal article" year="2014">
Sweetman 
<emphasis box="[645,700,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
) then assigned to 
<taxonomicName box="[317,452,1714,1741]" class="Actinopterygii" genus="Ocloedus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[317,413,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">Ocloedus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C." box="[467,646,1714,1740]" journalOrPublisher="Palaeobiodiversity and Palaeoenvironments" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" pagination="149 - 167" part="96" refId="ref49648" refString="SWEETMAN S. C. 2016. - A comparison of Barremian-early Aptian vertebrate assemblages from the Jehol Group, north-east China and the Wealden Group, southern Britain: the value of microvertebrate studies in adverse preservational settings. Palaeobiodiversity and Palaeoenvironments 96: 149 - 167. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12549 - 015 - 0217 - 9" title="A comparison of Barremian-early Aptian vertebrate assemblages from the Jehol Group, north-east China and the Wealden Group, southern Britain: the value of microvertebrate studies in adverse preservational settings" type="journal article" year="2016">Sweetman 2016</bibRefCitation>
). However, the English material includes nearly complete vomerine dentitions with three tooth rows (
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M." box="[522,768,1778,1804]" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" pagination="872 - 896" part="113" refId="ref49895" refString="SWEETMAN S. C., GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M. 2014. - A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 113: 872 - 896. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2011.0109" title="A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England" type="journal article" year="2014">
Sweetman 
<emphasis box="[645,701,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 10e), indicating that this unnamed species does not belong to either 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heckel" authorityYear="1856" box="[327,424,1841,1867]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pycnodontidae" genus="Coelodus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[327,424,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">Coelodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poyato-Ariza &amp; Wenz" authorityYear="2002" box="[468,565,1841,1867]" class="Actinopterygii" genus="Ocloedus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,565,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">Ocloedus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which both have five vomerine tooth rows (Poyato-Ariza &amp; Wenz 2002). Numerous ventral keel scales showing contacting spines of anteroposteriorly increasing size, can be assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1835" box="[132,302,1969,1995]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pycnodontidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Pycnodontidae</taxonomicName>
(see Poyato-Ariza &amp; Wenz 2002; 
<bibRefCitation author="SWEETMAN S. C. &amp; GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M." journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="12" pageNumber="693" pagination="872 - 896" part="113" refId="ref49895" refString="SWEETMAN S. C., GOEDERT J. &amp; MARTILL D. M. 2014. - A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 113: 872 - 896. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2011.0109" title="A preliminary account of the fishes of the Lower Cretaceous Wessex Formation (Wealden Group, Barremian) of the Isle of Wight, southern England" type="journal article" year="2014">
Sweetman 
<emphasis box="[189,243,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="693">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
